[normal]Written evidence from Freight on Rail (SRN 004)[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Freight on Rail thanks the Transport Select Committee for the opportunity to comment on its inquiry into the strategic road network.  We are commenting on 3 of the subject headings.
[normal]A [bold]How [bold]does the Government’s policy for roads link with planning for other transport modes[bold]1. 
[normal]The Government must 
[normal]look at 
[normal]multi-modal 
[normal]solutions along 
[normal]key strategic corridors with significant lorry traffic, in order to meet its economic, environmental and safety g
[normal]oals. 
[normal] Therefore it must 
[normal]consider rail freight options in the route based strategies and in the feasibility studies. Because r
[normal]oad and rail complement each other rail freight has a key role in helping the Government reduce road congestion
[normal] and meet its road
[normal] safety
[normal] and emissions
[normal] targets especially on key arterial freight routes. 
[normal]Rail 
[normal]can offer an alternative integrated solution for the T
[normal]ranspennine route, A303/A30 corridor, the A1 west and north of Newcastle and around Leeds
[normal].
[normal] Multi-modal transport options should be evaluated to  
[normal]address future problems including the five transport hotspots
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]2. 
[normal]Rail freight alternatives were assessed to some extent in the A14 corridor study
[normal]. 
[normal]In 2012, the intermodal analysis of the A14 corrido
[normal]r showed that there was considerable suppressed demand for rail out of the Felixstowe port because of the current limitations of the rail network and it highlighted the value of implementing rail capacity upgrades on the A14. These enhancements were subseq
[normal]uently included in the HLOS funding for the CP5 period. The evaluation showed that the extra capacity, would allow daily trains operations in and out of the port each day to increase from 30 to 50 which will increase rail’s market share increasing from 25%
[normal] to around 38%. Furthermore, these upgrades will result in the removal of 40 million long distance lorry miles from the A14 corridor per annum. 
[normal]3. 
[normal]Targeted rail freight upgrades work; rai
[normal]l’s market share out of Southampton port increased from 29-36% withi
[normal]n a year of completion of the gauge upgrade demonstrating the direct benefits of rail enhancements
[normal].
[normal]4. 
[normal]The CEO of HPUK, Clemence Cheung, told 
[normal]the Transport Select Committee hearing on Access to Ports
[normal] 
[normal]earlier in the year
[normal] that improved rail capacity was key
[normal] to Felixstowe port and would improve the competitive position of the port relative to ports such as Rotterdam. He said that less than three per cent of containers from the port were transported via the A14.
[normal]5. [bold]Work with rail freight industry [bold]to achieve [bold]in[bold]tegrated solution [bold]The DfT Roads directorate should work with Network Rail
[normal], the Focs, RFG
[normal] and the Rail Delivery Group to ensure that an integrated approach is adopted
[normal] on key corridors as r
[normal]ail freight links are an important driver of economic regeneration w
[normal]hich can help the Coalition Government meet its transport objective to promote the green sustainable economy with green jobs. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]RFG/RFOA commissioned rail freight forecasts which showed that  traffic overall is expected to double in the period between 2010
[normal] and 2030 with consumer traffic growing four fold.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]As you will be aware, Network Rail has undertaken a comprehensive Freight market study
[normal] which includes forecasts for growth, due to be released later this year which can be fed into these feasibility studies.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Planned [bold]r[bold]ail freight enhancements must be taken into account[bold]It is also crucial that the existing committed enhancements for the rail
[normal] network are taken into consideration when planning the strategic road network. The Government has committed to a series of upgrades in the Control Period 5 which must be taken into account. 
[normal]£200m for the Strategic (Rail) Freight Network (SFN)
[normal]Additionall
[normal]y, the following projects are the main schemes which will benefit freight and passenger services:- 
[normal]ii) Reconstruction of Ely North Junction 
[normal]iii) Leicester area capacity
[normal]iv) Electric Spin – Southampton Port to Basingstoke, Basingstoke – Reading- Oxford –B
[normal]anbury – Leamington Spa – Coventry
[normal]v) Capacity upgrades to the West and East Coast Mainline
[normal]vi) Great Western electrification
