[normal]B[bold]. How can we improve the reliability and efficiency of travel on the strategic road network?[bold]1. 
[normal]Shifting more freight to rail reduces road congestion
[normal] and exposure to road collisions 
[normal] 
[normal]w
[normal]hich c
[normal]rucially 
[normal]improves 
[normal]reliability as recognised by the Government Mode Shift grants system. The following statistics demonstrate the role rail has in alleviating road congestion; an average consumer freight train can remove up to 60 HGVs from our  roads 
[normal]and an aggregates train can remove up to 130 HGVs from our roads. 
[normal]2. [bold]Contradictions in DfT Freight Policy  [bold]However, p
[normal]olicies such as the  
[normal]DfT’s decision to allow trials of 7ft longer lorries, 
[normal]which its own research stated would 
[normal]undermine
[normal] rail freight a
[normal]nd
[normal] encourage more road freight
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]contradicts its stated policy to promote rail freight and reduce road collisions and pollution.  Because longer trailers will 
[normal]result in more external costs, more unreliability and more congestion on the strategic road network.
[normal]The DfT central case for longer trailers was built on the prediction that road operators will increase their share of goods traffic as a result of introducing longer lorries
[normal]. 
[normal]In particular, consumer rail freight
[normal] a key growth market
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]would
[normal],
[normal] using the DfT figures be severely undermined
[normal],
[normal] and forecasted growth would be cut by two thirds.
[normal]DfT research stated - [bold]Lower rail use [bold]was[bold] a major source of benefits in having longer trailers[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Between 27% to 32% of the environmental benefits of longer trail
[normal]ers are assumed to be gained by running fewer trains. By 2025 - 84% of the industry operational savings would be from lower rail costs. 
[normal]The assessment is very sensitive to the way that less rail traffic translates into fewer train kilometers and a realisti
[normal]c picture would be of external costs rising significantly. Also, if trains were electrified or became quieter, the benefits of not running them would fall and so would the benefits of longer trailers. 
[normal]Longer trailers would undermine low carbon energy-effi[bold]cient rail[bold], particularly the emerging supermarket (domestic intermodal) rail traffic, the sector with the highest growth potential of up to 12 
[normal]times in a 25 year period 
[normal]. Even the DfT figures states that the 2 metre trailer would reduce rail freight growt
[normal]h by two thirds (down from 732% to 262%) by 2025. This is because the relative costs of road and rail will be adversely affected by the new units, and rail will face a cost disadvantage; savings of up to 15% are predicted by some in the road haulage indust
[normal]ry. However the DfT suggest that this impact would be offset by rail operator being able to use longer intermodal units than at present, increasing their own efficiencies.  However, this assumes that customers will want to invest in such units, ahead of in
[normal]vesting in road fleet and also that the existing equipment, much of which is new, can be written off. All this is likely to result in a downward spiral for rail freight in this sector as critical mass is lost.
[normal]Longer trucks [bold]c[bold]ould mean more lorry miles not fewer [bold]because demand will be stimulated as longer trailers would reduce road haulage costs by up to 13%. Distribution centre are likely to be rationalised, saving on real estate costs, with lorry tonne kilometres increasing a
[normal]s the same freight is carried further.
[normal] 
[normal]The economic assumptions in the report are not realistic as they underestimate the extent to which longer vehicles will add to road mileage. 
[normal]Longer trailers will be slower to negotiate road junctions and add to road [bold]congestion[bold]The actual length of traffic lane occupied and the time that the lane is occupied needs to be fully taken into account. HGVs are considered to take up almost 4 times the space of an average car when stationery (passenger car units). Then one has
[normal] to allow for the fact that HGVs are slower to negotiate junctions and need longer front and rear headway than cars as braking distances are greater.
[normal]C  [bold]What mechanisms are there for Government to increase investment in strategic roads and attract new investors. [bold]A[bold]re there good examples from other countries that could be applied in the UK.[bold]1. [bold]Distance based lorry road user charging [bold]Freight on Rail 
[normal]supports
[normal] the principal of introducing a lorry road user charging system to ensure ensures fairer arrangements for the UK haulage industry. 
[normal]At present UK hauliers face unfair competition, with foreign hauliers not paying anything towards the costs of their use of U
[normal]K roads. 
[normal]However, we believe that the Government’s chosen time based system charges foreign hauliers too little, because of the EU restrictions, and 
[normal]could end up actually costing more in administration and enforcement than it raises. We believe that t
[normal]he Go
[normal]vernment should instead have gone for a distance-based charging scheme, as most European countries are now doing. This would charge foreign lorries properly for using UK roads, and would raise revenue that could be used to fund a more efficient and greener
[normal] UK freight industry. We therefore urge the Government to consider a comprehensive distance based system which could actually help reduce road congestion, emissions, accidents a
[normal]s well as raising revenue. 
[normal]Disadvantages of the Time based system [bold]being introd[bold]uced next April 2014[bold]Given that foreign hauliers only account for 6% of UK vehicle miles, the administrative burden of this 
[normal]scheme 
[normal]both for UK operators and DfT seems too high and could end up actually costing more in administration and enforcement than it
[normal] raises.
[normal]A simple but effective distance based  lorry road user charging scheme would therefore be fairer to UK hauliers but could also deliver wider objectives to:
[normal]• Improve road safety
[normal]• Reduce greenhouse gas emissions
[normal]• Minimise the external costs from 
[normal]heavy good vehicle traffic, including local air pollution, noise and congestion
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The experience from Europe shows that lorry road user charging schemes can be introduced, that the technology is proven and that this delivers significant benefits, particular
[normal]ly to support the economy and reduce climate change – the two main objectives in the new Government’s transport policies.
[normal] 
[normal]The German Maut system
[normal], developed within the Eurovignette guidelines, 
[normal]reduced empty running by 11% down to under 20%, increased rail f
[normal]reight by 7% and loaded runs by 2.1% in the ten year period up to 2010. 
[normal]http://www.bettertransport.org.uk/campaigns/climate_change/roads/lorry-user-charging
